Extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 to Complex Arguments
\layout Standard

The 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

may be generalized by taking the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

 to be a complex number.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

obvious
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 and reasonable generalization is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
b(s)=-s\gamma+\frac{1}{2}+\sum_{k=2}^{\infty}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
k\end{array}\right)\left[\zeta(k)-\frac{1}{k-1}\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

By construction, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $b(s)$
\end_inset 

 interpolates the previous series, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $b(n)=b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 for non-negative integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

.
 This function has a pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $s=-1$
\end_inset 

, and the above series expansion is convergent only for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s>-1$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

One may ask what form the analytic continuation of 
\begin_inset Formula $b(s)$
\end_inset 

 to the entire complex plane may look like.
 To examine this question, one makes use of two identities.
 
\layout Standard

First, one has 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}(-x)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
k\end{array}\right)=(1-x)^{s}\]

\end_inset 

 which holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x\right|<1$
\end_inset 

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 is a positive integer, the sum on the left clearly vanishes in the limit
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to1$
\end_inset 

, because the sum consists of a finite number of terms.
 That it also vanishes for any 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s>0$
\end_inset 

, follows from Carlson's theorem.
 The theorem applies because, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

, one can has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|s\log(1-x)\right|<\pi$
\end_inset 

 in the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to1$
\end_inset 

.
 Thus, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s>0$
\end_inset 

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{k=2}^{\infty}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
k\end{array}\right)=s-1\]

\end_inset 

 and one may take the right hand side to be the analytic continuation, to
 the entire complex plane, of the left hand side.
 
\layout Standard

Another important identity uses the digamma function
\begin_inset Formula \[
\psi(s)=\frac{d}{ds}\ln\Gamma(s)\]

\end_inset 

 to generalize the harmonic numbers
\begin_inset Formula \[
\psi(n)=H_{n-1}-\gamma\]

\end_inset 

 The digamma has a suitable binomial series [XXX ref for this formula?]
 valid for 
\begin_inset Formula $s>-1$
\end_inset 

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\psi(s+1)=-\gamma-\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
k\end{array}\right)\frac{1}{k}\]

\end_inset 

 As before, the uniqueness of this expansion may be argued by appeals to
 Carlson's theorem.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{k}=\frac{1}{k+1}+\frac{1}{k(k+1)}\]

\end_inset 

 and making use of the previous identity, one can readily show that, for
 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{k=2}^{\infty}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
k\end{array}\right)\frac{1}{k-1}=1+s\left(\gamma-1+\psi(s)\right)\]

\end_inset 

 
\layout Standard

Combining the above, one may write 
\begin_inset Formula $b(s)$
\end_inset 

 in a form that is regular on the entire complex plane 
\begin_inset Formula \[
b(s)=-\frac{3}{2}+s\left[2\left(1-\gamma\right)-\psi(s)\right]+\sum_{k=2}^{\infty}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
k\end{array}\right)\left[\zeta(k)-1\right]\]

\end_inset 

 The sum on the left is entire, having no poles except at infinity, and
 converges for all complex values of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

.
 That it is entire follows easily, as the sum is bounded:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\left|\sum_{k=2}^{\infty}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
k\end{array}\right)\left[\zeta(k)-1\right]\right| & < & 2\left|\sum_{k=2}^{\infty}\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s\\
k\end{array}\right)\left[\zeta(k)-1\right]\right|\\
 & \le & \left|2^{1-s}-2+s\right|\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

and thus, the sum cannot have any poles for finite 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

.
 The digamma is regular and single-valued on the complex plane, having simple
 poles at the negative integers; and thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $b(s)$
\end_inset 

 is likewise.
\layout Standard

