Finite Differences and the Norlund-Rice Integral
\layout Standard

This section reviews the the definition of the Norlund-Rice integral, and
 its application to finite differences and Newton series.
 Theorems required for convergence, and in particular, Carlson's theorem,
 are briefly stated.
 The next section applies these techniques to the evaluation of the finite
 differences of the Riemann zeta function.
\layout Lemma

(Norlund-Rice ?)
\layout Lemma

Given a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)$
\end_inset 

 holomorphic on a region containing the integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ n_{0},\cdots,n\}$
\end_inset 

, then the finite differences of the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ f(k)\}$
\end_inset 

 may be given an integral representation
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{k=n_{0}}^{n}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)(-1)^{k}f(k)=\frac{(-1)^{n}}{2\pi i}\oint_{\mathcal{C}}f(s)\frac{n!}{s(s-1)\cdots(s-n)}ds\]

\end_inset 

 where the contour of integration 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset 

encircles the integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ n_{0},\cdots,n\}$
\end_inset 

 in a positive direction, but does not include any of the integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1,\cdots,n_{0}-1\}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Proof

By residues.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Fla94}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Such sums commonly occur in the theory of finite differences.
 Given a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset 

, one defines its forward differences at point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a$
\end_inset 

 by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Delta^{n}\left[f\right](a)=\sum_{p=0}^{n}(-1)^{n-p}\binom{n}{p}\, f(p+a)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{n}{p}$
\end_inset 

 is the binomial coefficient.
 When one has only an arithmetic function or sequence of values 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{p}=f(p)$
\end_inset 

, rather than a function of a continuous variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

, the above is referred to as the binomial transform of the sequence.
 
\layout Standard

The forward differences may be used to construct the umbral calculus analog
 of a Taylor's series:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g(z+a)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\Delta^{n}\left[f\right](a)\;\frac{(z)_{n}}{n!}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $(z)_{n}=z(z-1)\ldots(z-n+1)$
\end_inset 

 is the Pochhammer symbol or falling factorial.
 When the growth rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 is suitably limited on the complex plane, then, by means of Carlson's Uniquenes
s theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $g=f$
\end_inset 

, and this series is known as the Newton series for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Theorem

(Carlson, 1914) If a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)$
\end_inset 

