The following section performs the asymptotic analysis for the Newton series
 of the Dirichlet 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

-functions; this section briefly reviews their definition.
 The Dirichlet 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

-functions
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Apo76}

\end_inset 

 are defined in terms of the Dirichlet characters, which are group representatio
n characters of the cyclic group.
 They play an important role in number theory, and the Riemann hypothesis
 generalizes to the 
\emph on 
L
\emph default 
-functions.
 The Dirichlet characters are multiplicative functions, and are periodic
 modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

.
 That is, a character 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi(n)$
\end_inset 

 is an arithmetic function of an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

, with period 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi(n+k)=\chi(n)$
\end_inset 

.
 A character is multiplicative, in that 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi(mn)=\chi(m)\chi(n)$
\end_inset 

 for all integers 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset 

.
 Furthermore, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi(1)=1$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi(n)=0$
\end_inset 

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd(n,k)\ne1$
\end_inset 

.
 The 
\emph on 
L
\emph default 
-function associated with the character 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset 

is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L(\chi,s)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{\chi(n)}{n^{s}}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 All such 
\emph on 
L
\emph default 
-functions may be re-expressed in terms of the Hurwitz zeta function as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L(\chi,s)=\frac{1}{k^{s}}\sum_{m=1}^{k}\chi(m)\zeta\left(s,\frac{m}{k}\right)\label{eq:L-Hurwitz}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

 is the period of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(s,q)$
\end_inset 

 is the Hurwitz zeta function, given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s,q)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(n+q)^{s}}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Thus, the study of the analytic properties of the 
\emph on 
L
\emph default 
-functions can be partially unified through the study of the Hurwitz zeta
 function.
\layout Section

Forward differences
\layout Standard

In analogy to the study of the forward differences of the Riemann zeta function,
 the remainder of this paper will concern itself with the analysis of the
 series given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L_{n}=\sum_{p=2}^{n}(-1)^{p}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
p\end{array}\right)\, L(\chi,p)\label{eq:L-coeff}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Because of the relation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:L-Hurwitz}

\end_inset 

 connecting the Hurwitz zeta function to the L-function, it is sufficient
 to study sums of the form
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A_{n}(m,k)=\sum_{p=2}^{n}(-1)^{p}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
p\end{array}\right)\,\frac{\zeta\left(p,\frac{m}{k}\right)}{k^{p}}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 since 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L_{n}=\sum_{m=1}^{k}\chi(m)\, A_{n}(m,k)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Converting the sum to the Norlund-Rice integral, and extending the contour
 to the half-circle at positive infinity, and noting that the half-circle
 does not contribute to the integral, one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A_{n}(m,k)=\frac{(-1)^{n}}{2\pi i}\, n!\,\int_{\frac{3}{2}-i\infty}^{\frac{3}{2}+i\infty}\frac{\zeta\left(s,\frac{m}{k}\right)}{k^{s}s(s-1)\cdots(s-n)}\, ds\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Moving the integral to the left, one encounters single pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0$
\end_inset 

 and a double pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1$
\end_inset 

.
 The residue of the pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0$
\end_inset 

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mbox{Res}(s=0)=\zeta\left(0,\frac{m}{k}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where one has the curious identity in the form of a multiplication theorem
 for the digamma function:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta\left(0,\frac{m}{k}\right)=\frac{-1}{\pi k}\sum_{p=1}^{k}\sin\left(\frac{2\pi pm}{k}\right)\psi\left(\frac{p}{k}\right)=-B_{1}\left(\frac{m}{k}\right)=\frac{1}{2}-\frac{m}{k}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset 

 is the digamma function and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset 

is the Bernoulli polynomial of order 1.
 The double pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1$
\end_inset 

 evaluates to
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mbox{Res}(s=1)=\frac{n}{k}\left[\psi\left(\frac{m}{k}\right)+\ln k+1-H_{n-1}\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Combining these, one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A_{n}(m,k)=\left(\frac{m}{k}-\frac{1}{2}\right)-\frac{n}{k}\left[\psi\left(\frac{m}{k}\right)+\ln k+1-H_{n-1}\right]+a_{n}(m,k)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The remaining term has the remarkable property of being exponentially small;
 that is, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a_{n}(m,k)=\mathcal{O}\left(e^{-\sqrt{Kn}}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 for a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset 

 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $m/k$
\end_inset 

.
 The next section develops an explicit asymptotic form for this term.
\layout Section

Saddle-point methods
\layout Standard

The term 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}(m,k)$
\end_inset 

 is represented by the integral
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a_{n}(m,k)=\frac{(-1)^{n}}{2\pi i}\, n!\,\int_{-\frac{1}{2}-i\infty}^{-\frac{1}{2}+i\infty}\frac{\zeta\left(s,\frac{m}{k}\right)}{k^{s}s(s-1)\cdots(s-n)}\, ds\label{eq:little-a-integral}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 which resulted from shifting the integration contour past the poles.
 At this point, the functional equation for the Hurwitz zeta may be applied.
 This equation is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta\left(1-s,\frac{m}{k}\right)=\frac{2\Gamma(s)}{(2\pi k)^{s}}\sum_{p=1}^{k}\cos\left(\frac{\pi s}{2}-\frac{2\pi pm}{k}\right)\zeta\left(s,\frac{p}{k}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 This allows the integral to be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a_{n}(m,k)=-\frac{n!}{k\pi i}\sum_{p=1}^{k}\int_{\frac{3}{2}-i\infty}^{\frac{3}{2}+i\infty}\frac{1}{(2\pi)^{s}}\frac{\Gamma(s)\Gamma(s-1)}{\Gamma(s+n)}\cos\left(\frac{\pi s}{2}-\frac{2\pi pm}{k}\right)\zeta\left(s,\frac{p}{k}\right)\, ds\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 It will prove to be convenient to pull the phase factor out of the cosine
 part; we do this now, and write this integral as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
a_{n}(m,k) & = & -\frac{n!}{2k\pi i}\sum_{p=1}^{k}\exp\left(i\frac{2\pi pm}{k}\right)\int_{\frac{3}{2}-i\infty}^{\frac{3}{2}+i\infty}\frac{1}{(2\pi)^{s}}\frac{\Gamma(s)\Gamma(s-1)}{\Gamma(s+n)}\,\exp\left(-i\frac{\pi s}{2}\right)\zeta\left(s,\frac{p}{k}\right)\, ds\label{eq:two-integrals}\\
 &  & +c.c.\nonumber \end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c.c.$
\end_inset 

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset 

 should be replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $-i$
\end_inset 

 in the two exp parts.
\layout Standard

For large values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

, this integral may be evaluated by means of the saddle-point method.
 The saddle-point method, or method of steepest descents, may be applied
 whenever the integrand can be approximated by a sharply peaked Gaussian,
 as the above can be for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

.
 More precisely, The saddle-point theorem states that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int e^{-Nf(x)}dx\approx\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{N\left|f^{\,\prime\prime}(x_{0})\right|}}e^{-Nf(x_{0})}\left[1-\frac{f^{(4)}(x_{0})}{8N\left|f^{\,\prime\prime}(x_{0})\right|^{2}}+\cdots\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 is an asymptotic expansion for large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset 

.
 Here, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 is taken to have a local minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x_{0}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\,\prime\prime}(x_{0})$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{(4)}(x_{0})$
\end_inset 

 are the second and fourth derivatives at the local minimum.
 
\layout Standard

To recast the equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:two-integrals}

\end_inset 

 into the form needed for the method of steepest descents, an asymptotic
 expansion of the integrands will need to be made for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

.
 After such an expansion, it is seen that the saddle point occurs at large
 values of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

, and so an asymptotic expansion in large 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 is warranted as well.
 As it is confusing and laborious to simultaneously expand in two parameters,
 it is better to seek out an order parameter to couple the two.
 This may be done as follows.
 One notes that the integrands have a minimum, on the real 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 axis, near 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\sigma_{0}=\sqrt{\pi pn/k}$
\end_inset 

 and so the appropriate scaling parameter is 
\begin_inset Formula $z=s/\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset 

.
 One should then immediately perform a change of variable from 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

.
 The asymptotic expansion is then performed by holding 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

 constant, and taking 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

 large.
 Thus, one writes 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
a_{n}(m,k) & = & -\frac{1}{2k\pi i}\sum_{p=1}^{k}\left[\exp\left(i\frac{2\pi pm}{k}\right)\int_{\sigma_{0}-i\infty}^{\sigma_{0}+i\infty}e^{f(z)}dz\right.\label{eq:saddle}\\
 &  & \left.+\exp\left(-i\frac{2\pi pm}{k}\right)\int_{\sigma_{0}-i\infty}^{\sigma_{0}+i\infty}e^{\overline{f}(z)}dz\right]\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset 

 is the complex conjugate of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

Proceeding, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
f(z)=\log n!+\frac{1}{2}\log n+\phi\left(z\sqrt{n}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\phi(s)=-s\log\left(\frac{2\pi p}{k}\right)-i\frac{\pi s}{2}+\log\frac{\Gamma(s)\Gamma(s-1)}{\Gamma(s+n)}+\mathcal{O}\left(\left(\frac{p}{k+p}\right)^{s}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where the approximation that 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\left(s,p/k\right)=(k/p)^{s}+\mathcal{O}\left((p/(k+p))^{s}\right)$
\end_inset 

 for large 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 has been made.
 More generally, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\log\zeta(s)=\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}\;\frac{\Lambda(n)}{n^{s}\log n}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda(n)$
\end_inset 

 is the von Mangoldt function.
 (XXX What about Hurwitz?) The asymptotic expansion for the Gamma function
 is given by the Stirling expansion, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\log\Gamma(x)=\left(x-\frac{1}{2}\right)\log x-x+\frac{1}{2}\log2\pi+\sum_{j=1}^{\infty}\frac{B_{2j}}{2j(2j-1)x^{2j-1}}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{k}$
\end_inset 

 are the Bernoulli numbers.
 Expanding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(1/n)$
\end_inset 

 and collecting terms, one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
f(z) & = & \frac{1}{2}\log n-z\sqrt{n}\left[\log\frac{2\pi p}{k}+i\frac{\pi}{2}+2-2\log z\right]\nonumber \\
 &  & +\log2\pi-2\log z-\frac{z^{2}}{2}\label{eq:}\\
 &  & +\frac{1}{6z\sqrt{n}}\left[10+z^{2}\right]+\frac{1}{2n}\left[1-\frac{z^{2}}{2}-\frac{z^{4}}{6}+\frac{73}{72z^{2}}\right]+\mathcal{O}\left(n^{-3/2}\right)\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 The saddle point may be obtained by solving 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\,\prime}(z)=0$
\end_inset 

.
 To lowest order, one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0}=(1+i)\sqrt{\pi p/k}$
\end_inset 

.
 To use the saddle-point formula, one needs 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\,\prime\prime}(z)=2\sqrt{n}/z+\mathcal{O}(1)$
\end_inset 

.
 Substituting, one directly obtains 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\int_{\sigma_{0}-i\infty}^{\sigma_{0}+i\infty}e^{f(z)}dz & = & \left(\frac{2\pi^{3}pn}{k}\right)^{1/4}e^{i\pi/8}\exp\left(-(1+i)\sqrt{\frac{4\pi pn}{k}}\right)\label{eq:}\\
 &  & \quad\quad\qquad+\mathcal{O}\left(n^{-1/4}e^{-2\sqrt{\pi pn/k}}\right)\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 while the integral for 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{f}$
\end_inset 

 is the complex conjugate of this (having a saddle point at the complex
 conjugate location).
 Inserting this into equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:saddle}

\end_inset 

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
a_{n}(m,k) & = & \frac{1}{k}\left(\frac{2n}{\pi}\right)^{1/4}\sum_{p=1}^{k}\left(\frac{p}{k}\right)^{1/4}\exp\left(-\sqrt{\frac{4\pi pn}{k}}\right)\cos\left(\sqrt{\frac{4\pi pn}{k}}-\frac{5\pi}{8}-\frac{2\pi pm}{k}\right)\label{eq:an-p}\\
 &  & \qquad\qquad+\mathcal{O}\left(n^{-1/4}e^{-2\sqrt{\pi pn/k}}\right)\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

For large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

, only the 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset 

 term contributes significantly, and so one may write
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
a_{n}(m,k) & = & \frac{1}{k}\left(\frac{2n}{\pi k}\right)^{1/4}\exp\left(-\sqrt{\frac{4\pi n}{k}}\right)\cos\left(\sqrt{\frac{4\pi n}{k}}-\frac{5\pi}{8}-\frac{2\pi m}{k}\right)\label{eq:}\\
 &  & \qquad\quad+\mathcal{O}\left(n^{-1/4}e^{-2\sqrt{\pi n/k}}\right)\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 which demonstrates the desired result: the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are exponentially small.
\layout Standard

The consistency of these results, with respect to the previous derivation
 for the Riemann zeta can be checked inn several ways.
 First, one may make the direct substitution 
\begin_inset Formula $m=k=1$
\end_inset 

 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
b_{n}=a_{n}(1,1)=\left(\frac{2n}{\pi}\right)^{1/4}\exp\left(-\sqrt{4\pi n}\right)\cos\left(\sqrt{4\pi n}-\frac{5\pi}{8}\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(n^{-1/4}e^{-2\sqrt{\pi n}}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Alternately, the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

multiplication theorem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 for the Hurwitz zeta states that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{m=1}^{k}\zeta\left(s,\frac{m}{k}\right)=k^{s}\zeta(s)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 from which one may deduce both that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{k=1}^{m}A_{n}(m,k)=\sum_{p=2}^{n}(-1)^{p}\binom{n}{p}\zeta(p)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{k=1}^{m}a_{n}(m,k)=b_{n}\label{eq:consistency}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 In particular, the above must hold order by order in the asymptotic expansion.
 The correctness of the expansion given by equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:an-p}

\end_inset 

 with regards to this identity may be readily verified by substitution.
 An important special case of equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:consistency}

\end_inset 

 is the relation 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a_{n}(2,2)=b_{n}-a_{n}(1,2)=\sum_{p=2}^{n}(-1)^{p}\binom{n}{p}\left(1-2^{-p}\right)\zeta(p)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 which appears often in the literature [Coffey].
 It has the asymptotic expansion 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a_{n}(2,2)=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{p=1}^{2}\left(\frac{np}{\pi}\right)^{1/4}\exp\left(-\sqrt{2\pi np}\right)\cos\left(\sqrt{2\pi np}-\frac{5\pi}{8}\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(n^{-1/4}e^{-\sqrt{2\pi n}}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

