More L-functions
\layout Standard

We conclude by briefly returning to the structure of the Dirichlet L-functions.
 The L-function coefficients defined in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:L-coeff}

\end_inset 

 are now given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L_{n}=\sum_{m=1}^{k}\chi(m)A_{n}(m,k)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A_{n}=B_{n}+a_{n}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{n}(m,k)$
\end_inset 

represents the non-exponential part, one may state a few results.
 For the non-principal characters, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{m=1}^{k}\chi(m)=0$
\end_inset 

 and thus, the first term simplifies to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{m=1}^{k}\chi(m)B_{n}(m,k)=\frac{1}{k}\sum_{m=1}^{k}\chi(m)\left[m-n\psi\left(\frac{m}{k}\right)\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 For the principal character 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{1}$
\end_inset 

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{m=1}^{k}\chi_{1}(m)=\varphi(k)$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(k)$
\end_inset 

 the Euler Totient function.
 Thus, for the principal character, one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\sum_{m=1}^{k}\chi_{1}(m)B_{n}(m,k) & = & -\varphi(k)\left[\frac{1}{2}+\frac{n}{k}\left(\ln k+1-H_{n-1}\right)\right]\label{eq:}\\
 &  & \qquad+\frac{1}{k}\sum_{m=1}^{k}\chi_{1}(m)\left[m-n\psi\left(\frac{m}{k}\right)\right]\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

By contrast, the exponentially small term invokes a linear combination of
 Gauss sums.
 The Gauss sum associated with a character 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset 

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G(n,\chi)=\sum_{m\mbox{ mod}k}\chi(m)e^{2\pi imn/k}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and so, to leading order 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\sum_{m=1}^{k}\chi(m)a_{n}(m,k) & = & \frac{1}{2k}\sum_{p=1}^{k}\left(\frac{2pn}{\pi k}\right)^{1/4}\exp\left(-\sqrt{\frac{4\pi pn}{k}}\right)\times\nonumber \\
 &  & \quad\left[\exp i\left(\frac{5\pi}{8}-\sqrt{\frac{4\pi pn}{k}}\right)G(p,\chi)\right.\label{eq:}\\
 &  & \qquad\quad\left.+\exp-i\left(\frac{5\pi}{8}-\sqrt{\frac{4\pi pn}{k}}\right)G(-p,\chi)\right]\\
 &  & \quad+\mathcal{O}\left(n^{-1/4}e^{-2\sqrt{\pi n/k}}\right)\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

The above expression simplifies slightly for the principle character, since
 one has the identities 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G\left(1,\chi_{1}\right)=\mu(k)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(k)$
\end_inset 

 the Mobius function and more generally, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G\left(p,\chi_{1}\right)=\frac{\varphi(k)\mu\left(\frac{k}{(p,k)}\right)}{\varphi\left(\frac{k}{(p,k)}\right)}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 
\layout Standard

