The asymptotic behavior of the 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}$
\end_inset 

 can be obtained by the corresponding Norlund-Rice integral.
 That is, one writes 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
d_{n}=\frac{(-1)^{n-1}}{2\pi i}\int_{3/2-i\infty}^{3/2+i\infty}\frac{1}{\zeta(s)}\,\frac{n!}{s(s-1)(s-2)\cdots(s-n)}ds\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The contour may be closed to the left, and the Cauchy-Riemann theorem applied.
 The integral has poles at zero, at the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

trivial zeroes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $-2k$
\end_inset 

, and at the non-trivial zeroes 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\sigma+i\tau$
\end_inset 

.
 Thus, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
d_{n}=-\frac{1}{\zeta(0)}+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{n!\,(2k-1)!}{(2k+n)!}\,\frac{1}{\zeta^{\prime}(-2k)}+c_{n}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where the non-trivial zeros contribute
\begin_inset Formula \[
c_{n}=\left(-1\right)^{n}\sum_{\rho}\frac{n!}{\rho(\rho-1)\cdots(\rho-n)}\,\frac{1}{\zeta^{\prime}(\rho)}\]

\end_inset 

Substituting for 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta^{\prime}(-2k)=\left(-1\right)^{k}\,\frac{(2k)!}{2(2\pi)^{2k}}\,\zeta(2k+1)\]

\end_inset 

 one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
d_{n}=-\frac{1}{\zeta(0)}+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\left(-1\right)^{k}\frac{n!}{(2k+n)!}\,\frac{(2\pi)^{2k}}{k\zeta(2k+1)}+c_{n}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The value of zeta at zero, 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(0)=-1/2$
\end_inset 

 accounts fully for the low-
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

 behavior seen in the numerical sums.
 The next few terms in the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

 summation provide corrections that die away rapidly for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

, and thus aren't particularly interesting.
 The contribution of the non-trivial zeros is more surprising.
 One has
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
c_{n}=-\sum_{\rho}\frac{\Gamma(n+1)\Gamma(-\rho)}{\Gamma(n-\rho+1)}\,\frac{1}{\zeta^{\prime}(\rho)}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 For large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

, the Stirling approximation may be applied.
 The sum has two distinct regimes.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\sigma+i\tau$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=1/2$
\end_inset 

 if the Riemann Hypothesis is assumed.
 One may then consider the sum for the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\ll n$
\end_inset 

, and the case where this does not hold.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{n}=\alpha_{n}+\beta_{n}$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{n}$
\end_inset 

 for the first few terms of the sum, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{n}$
\end_inset 

 for the remaining terms, one then has, after applying the Stirling approximatio
n, that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\alpha_{n}=-\left[1+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\right]\sum_{\tau\ll n}\left(n+1\right)^{\sigma}\frac{\Gamma\left(-\sigma-i\tau\right)}{\zeta^{\prime}\left(\sigma+i\tau\right)}e^{i\tau\log\left(n+1\right)}\label{eq: alpha_n}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Assuming the Riemann hypothesis, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=1/2$
\end_inset 

, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{n}=\mathcal{O}\left(\sqrt{n}\right)$
\end_inset 

.
 This is suppressed by a small factor, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Gamma(\frac{1}{2}+i\tau)\right|\sim e^{-\tau\pi/2}$
\end_inset 

.
 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{n}$
\end_inset 

 is also slowly oscillatory.
 The remaining terms take the form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\beta_{n} & =-\left[1+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)\right] & \sqrt{2\pi}\sum_{\tau\gtrsim n}\sqrt{\frac{\tau+in}{\tau n}}\times\\
 &  & \exp\left[\frac{n+1}{2}\log\left(\frac{n^{2}}{n^{2}+\tau^{2}}\right)+\frac{\sigma}{2}\log\left(1+\frac{n^{2}}{\tau^{2}}\right)-\tau\arctan\frac{n}{\tau}\right]\times\\
 &  & \exp i\left[\left(n+1\right)\arctan\frac{\tau}{n}+\frac{\tau}{2}\log\left(1+\frac{n^{2}}{\tau^{2}}\right)\right]\times\frac{1}{\zeta^{\prime}(\rho)}\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

Since one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\log n^{2}/(n^{2}+\tau^{2})<0$
\end_inset 

, one has that the remaining terms in the sum are exponentially small, provided
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta^{\prime}(\rho)$
\end_inset 

 never becomes arbitrarily small.
 Since the number of non-trivial zeros of the Riemann zeta does not increase
 exponentially, the sum can be estimated, and one concludes that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\beta_{n}=\mathcal{O}\left(e^{-Kn}\right)\label{eq:beta-n estimate}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $K>0$
\end_inset 

.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset 

 can be bounded away from zero, simply by arranging which terms are grouped
 into the finite sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{n}$
\end_inset 

, and which are not.
 Thus, for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

, the contribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{n}$
\end_inset 

 can be ignored, and the asymptotic form of 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}$
\end_inset 

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
d_{n}=2+\alpha_{n}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}\right)\]

\end_inset 

 where the Riemann hypothesis is assumed, so that a term 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset 

 can be brought out of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{n}$
\end_inset 

.
 Since one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Gamma(\frac{1}{2}+i\tau)\right|\sim e^{-\tau\pi/2}$
\end_inset 

, each term contributing to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{n}$
\end_inset 

 is considerably smaller than the last.
 Summing together the zeros above and below the real axis, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
d_{n}=2-2\sqrt{n+1}\sum_{n\gg\tau>0}\Re\left[\frac{\Gamma\left(-\frac{1}{2}-i\tau\right)e^{i\tau\log(n+1)}}{\zeta^{\prime}\left(\frac{1}{2}+i\tau\right)}\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The leading contribution to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{n}$
\end_inset 

 is given by the first zero at 
