\layout Subsection

Equivalence to the Riemann Hypothesis 
\layout Standard

What is curious about this result is that, if the Riemann Hypothesis holds,
 then there are no further corrections to this asymptotic behavior.
 The first zero gives the dominant term, and the second and subsequent zeroes
 give corrections that are at least 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-5}$
\end_inset 

 smaller, but of the same order in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

.
 If there is a non-trivial zero that is not on the critical line, then it
 will contribute to equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq: alpha_n}

\end_inset 

 with a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{broke}\ne1/2$
\end_inset 

, and so one will instead have 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}=\mathcal{O}\left(n^{\sigma_{broke}}\right)$
\end_inset 

.
 However, the contribution of such a zero would be strongly suppressed,
 by a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-\pi\tau/2}$
\end_inset 

.
 Since the Riemann hypothesis has been verified to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\sim10^{12}$
\end_inset 

, the deviation from the square-root behavior would be numerically inaccessible.
 At any rate, the above sketch demonstrates that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}=\mathcal{O}\left(\sqrt{n}\right)$
\end_inset 

 is equivalent to the Riemann Hypothesis.
 
\layout Standard

This conclusion generalizes almost trivially to the Generalized Riemann
 Hypothesis for the Dirichlet 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

-functions.
 Each of the equations in the previous section hold under the substitution
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\prime}(s,\chi)$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta^{\prime}(s)$
\end_inset 

.
 The only tricky step of the proof, which was glossed over and left unsupported
 above, was the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta^{\prime}(\rho)$
\end_inset 

 is never small, that is, that its bounded away from zero, so that the argument
 about the non-importance of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{n}$
\end_inset 

 holds.
 Provided that one can show this (and similarly, that 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\prime}(s,\chi)$
\end_inset 

 is never small), then the argument follows through for the Generalized
 Riemann Hypothesis as well.
\layout Standard

The above casual derivation can be inverted to show that the Riemann Hypothesis
 implies that the derivatives are bounded away from zero.
 It may be rigirously shown
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Fla06}

\end_inset 

 that the RH is equivalent to having 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}=\mathcal{O}\left(n^{1/2+\epsilon}\right)$
\end_inset 

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset 

.
 To reconcile this with the above sketch that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}=\mathcal{O}\left(\sqrt{n}\right)$
\end_inset 

, one must conclude that, for all but possibly a finite set of zeroes 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset 

, one must have 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left|\zeta^{\prime}(\rho)\right|>\mathcal{O}\left(e^{-\tau\pi/2}\right)\]

\end_inset 

 as otherwise the estimates for equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:beta-n estimate}

\end_inset 

 would fail.
