\layout Subsection

Liouville series
\layout Standard

Let 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
d_{n}^{\lambda}=\sum_{k=2}^{n}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\,\frac{\zeta(2k)}{\zeta(k)}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

be the series corresponding to the Liouville function.
 The integrand of the corresponding Norlund-Rice integral is regular at
 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1$
\end_inset 

 and has a simple pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $2s=1$
\end_inset 

 and another at 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0$
\end_inset 

.
 In other respects, it resembles the integral formulation for the Mobius
 series.
 The simple pole contributes a term of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{n})$
\end_inset 

.
 Curiously, there are no poles from the trivial zeros, as these are balanced
 out by the numerator.
 The contribution of the non-trivial zeroes to the sum may be estimated
 as in the Mobius sum.
 
