\layout Section

Relation to literature
\layout Standard

The following is a list of Newton series or other suggestive sums or integrals
 that occur in the literature, both modern and older.
 Many of these may be amenable to the techniques given above, or have results
 that follow immediately from the above.
\layout Subsection

Reciprocal Riemann Zeta
\layout Standard

The Riemann zeta function has regularly-spaced zeros along the negative
 real axis.
 Thus, the reciprocal has poles at the (even) integers, and thus resembles
 the Norlund-Rice integrand.
 Viz: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\oint_{C}\frac{ds}{\zeta(s)}\sim\sum\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\frac{1}{\zeta^{\prime}(2n)}\]

\end_inset 

 where the contour encircles 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

 poles.
 Not clear how to turn the integral into something suitable for a saddle-point
 method.
 
\layout Subsection

Maslanka/Baez-Duarte
\layout Standard

A similar sum appears in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Ba03}

\end_inset 

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
c_{n}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\frac{1}{\zeta(2k+2)}\]

\end_inset 

 and furthermore, it is claimed that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
c_{n}\ll n^{-3/4+\epsilon}\forall\epsilon>0\]

\end_inset 

 is equivalent to RH.
 Note the summand is just a ratio of Bernoulli numbers and powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset 

.
