The paper concludes by noting the general resemblance of the asymptotic
 behavior to that of two other famous number-theoretic sequences.
 The partition function 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset 

is given by Euler's infinite product
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Apo90}

\end_inset 

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}p_{n}x^{n}=\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{1-x^{m}}\]

\end_inset 

 and for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

, takes on the asymptotic form 
\begin_inset Formula \[
p_{n}\sim\frac{\exp K\sqrt{n}}{4n\sqrt{3}}\]

\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\pi\sqrt{2/3}$
\end_inset 

.
 This form was given by Hardy and Ramanujan [ref] and Uspensky [ref], with
 a full series valid to all orders given by Rademacher[ref].
 There is a similar asymptotic form for the Fourier coefficients of the
 modular 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

-invariant,
\begin_inset Formula \[
j(\tau)=e^{-2\pi i\tau}+\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}c_{n}e^{2\pi in\tau}\]

\end_inset 

 where the coefficients take on the asymptotic values
\begin_inset Formula \[
c_{n}\sim\frac{\exp4\pi\sqrt{n}}{n^{3/4}\sqrt{2}}\]

\end_inset 

 which was given by Petersson [ref]
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Apo90}

\end_inset 

.
 The appearance of an asymptotic factor in the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{K\sqrt{n}}$
\end_inset 

 here and in the Newton series is suggestive.
 However, unlike the 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset 

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{n}$
\end_inset 

, the values 
\begin_inset Formula $1/b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are not integers; nor is the Fourier series 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n}x^{n}/b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 a modular form.
 
